source: This allows the player to play through the single-player missions with up to four other people taking the place of computer-controlled SWAT officers. In the expansion, Co-op can run on custom missions and with up to ten players per game, which can further be split into two completely separate teams (red and blue) with a leader each. This is not similar to single player teams where an element leader controls both teams.

911: 911, do you need Police, Fire, or Medic?
Caller: Police, there are people robbing this store.
911: OK, there are people robbing the store. Where are you, ma’am?
Caller: I’m in the.. I’m in the restroom. The women’s restroom. 
911: Have you been injured? Are you with anybody else?
Caller: No, I’m alone. My baby girl is outside somewhere. She ran away from me.
911: OK ma’am. You’re in the restroom and you’re saying you have a little girl with you?
Caller: No, she’s not with me. I don’t know where she is.
911: That’s okay, that’s okay. So what we’re going to do is get you to sit tight. Officers are on the way.
Caller: Please hurry. My girl could be anywhere.
[Gunshots and yelling heard faintly over phone]
911: Ma’am, are you okay? Ma’am?
Caller: They just killed somebody. They just killed somebody. I think it was a clerk.
911: OK I’m going to stay with you until the police arrive, alright?

After flunking school, Prescott joined the police force under the advice that it would save face. Originally reluctant, Prescott enjoyed the authority gained with policing and fell in love with the force and the people he served with. Prescott’s aggressive yet caring demeanour and impressive marksmanship was noted to be suitable for SWAT forces, thus landing him a role in the Squad. Prescott’s main interest outside of policing is sport, an activity he was successful at during his schooling.

After uncovering an old shipment of late cold war weapons, the department's armorer took to refurbishing the weapon in hopes of reselling them to the highest bidder. With a clear lack of public interest in the weapons, they were placed in the station's storage unit.

When a band of gang members assaulted the department's precinct to avenge their murdered leader, the AR-18 found great use in fending off these attackers due to its quick fire rate and fast muzzle velocity.

On the fringes of the inner city, Cowboy’s family beared witness to multiple armed robberies and race riots in the mid 1990s. Born and raised in heartland of Gainesville, Florida; Robert Childs was raised in a typical all-American, lower middle class family where his father, Jonathan Childs, was a long serving street officer for the better part of 30 years on the beat. Southern born and raised, ‘Alabama’ lived in near poverty with his devoted Christian single mother. Resisting the pressure to fall into delinquency like his fellow peers, Alabama spent his time reading books and playing video games, which his mother saved up to buy. His interest in history and machinery, especially cars and firearms, led him to join the Marines.  After a tour in Afghanistan, Alabama and his mother moved to the city where he joined the police force. His combat experience was noted and was requested to join SWAT after only a year and a half as a sworn officer.
